Azure provides three messaging and event services that serve distinct purposes. Azure Service Bus is an enterprise message broker — it guarantees ordered, transactional, reliable delivery of messages between application components, equivalent to A-W-S S-Q-S and S-N-S combined. Azure Event Grid is an event router — it delivers lightweight notifications that something happened in near real time, routing them to many subscribers, equivalent to Amazon EventBridge. Azure Event Hubs is an event streaming service — it ingests millions of events per second, retains them for replay, and feeds analytics pipelines, equivalent to Amazon Kinesis.

The key conceptual distinction is this. Service Bus carries messages — data with instructions to act on — and guarantees delivery, ordering, and transactions for critical business workflows. Event Grid carries events — small notifications that something happened — and routes them to many handlers at low cost. Event Hubs carries streams — high-volume sequential data — that can be retained and replayed by multiple independent consumers.

Let us start with Azure Service Bus.

Service Bus is a fully managed enterprise message broker. All queues and topics live inside a namespace. There are three tiers. The Basic tier supports queues only with 256-kilobyte messages and is suitable for development and testing. The Standard tier adds topics and subscriptions. The Premium tier supports messages up to 100 megabytes, V-Net integration, private endpoints, and geo-disaster recovery — it is the right tier for production workloads with large messages or compliance requirements.

A queue provides point-to-point messaging. One or more producers send messages to the queue, and one or more competing consumers receive from it — but each message is delivered to only one consumer. This is the standard pattern for distributing work across a pool of workers. Messages have a configurable T-T-L — the default is 14 days. The lock duration determines how long a consumer has to process a message before it becomes visible again. The max delivery count limits how many times a message is retried before it is moved to the dead-letter queue.

A topic provides publish-subscribe messaging. Producers send to the topic, and multiple subscriptions each receive their own copy of every message. This allows a single published event to drive multiple independent downstream processes — for example, an order placed event could go to the email subscription, the inventory subscription, and the analytics subscription simultaneously.

Each subscription can have filters to receive only a subset of messages. SQL filters use a SQL-like expression on message properties — for example, priority equals high. Correlation filters match on specific property values and are faster than SQL filters. Boolean filters are either True-Filter to receive everything or False-Filter to receive nothing, used for temporarily disabling a subscription.

Service Bus uses a peek-lock model for message receipt. When a consumer receives a message, the message is locked and made invisible to other consumers for the lock duration. The consumer then settles the message in one of four ways. Complete means processing succeeded and the message is deleted from the queue. Abandon releases the lock so another consumer can retry the message. Dead-letter moves the message permanently to the dead-letter queue for manual inspection. And Defer parks the message so the consumer can retrieve it later by its sequence number — useful when a message arrives out of order and needs to be processed after its dependencies.

Every queue and subscription has a built-in dead-letter queue. Messages land here when the delivery count exceeds the maximum, when the T-T-L expires before processing, when the consumer explicitly dead-letters the message, or when a filter evaluation error occurs. A growing dead-letter queue in production always indicates a processing problem that needs investigation.

Service Bus sessions group related messages under a shared Session I-D. All messages with the same Session I-D are processed by a single consumer in order, enabling stateful workflows. For example, all messages for a given order or customer can be guaranteed to be processed sequentially by the same consumer instance.

Additional advanced features include scheduled messages that are delivered at a future time, duplicate detection that discards messages with duplicate I-Ds within a configurable time window, transactions that allow atomic operations across multiple entities in the same namespace, and geo-disaster recovery that replicates namespace metadata to a secondary region so the namespace can fail over if the primary region goes down.

Now let us look at Azure Event Grid.

Azure Event Grid is a fully managed event routing service. It delivers lightweight event notifications from sources to handlers in near real time with no polling and a pay-per-event pricing model. The flow is: an event source publishes an event to a topic, Event Grid matches the event against subscriptions, filters are applied, and matching events are delivered to the configured handler.

Event sources come in several types. System topics provide built-in events from Azure services — for example, Blob Storage generates a Microsoft dot Storage dot BlobCreated event whenever a blob is uploaded, and Resource Groups generate events whenever resources are created or deleted. Custom topics allow your own application to publish events to an Event Grid endpoint. Partner topics bring in events from external S-a-a-S platforms such as Salesforce, S-A-P, and Auth0.

Each event is a small J-S-O-N object with a standard envelope: an I-D, the source resource, the event type, the timestamp, and a data payload. Event types follow a dot-separated naming convention like Microsoft dot Storage dot BlobCreated or your own MyApp dot Order dot Placed.

Event handlers are the destinations that receive events. Azure Functions is the most common handler — it processes events serverlessly. Logic Apps enable low-code workflow automation. Event Hubs can act as a handler to buffer events for stream processing. Service Bus provides reliable delivery with a dead-letter queue. Storage Queues offer simple durable delivery. And webhooks allow any H-T-T-P-S endpoint to receive events.

An event subscription filters which events reach a handler. You can filter by event type, by the subject using prefix or suffix matching — for example only blobs in a specific container — or by advanced filters on event data fields using operators such as equals, contains, or begins-with.

Event Grid retries delivery using exponential backoff for up to 24 hours by default. After all retries are exhausted, events can be forwarded to a dead-letter storage container in Blob Storage for later inspection. Event Grid guarantees at-least-once delivery — handlers must be idempotent.

The key differences between Event Grid and Service Bus are that Event Grid is designed for reactive event notifications with a 24-hour retry window and no ordering guarantee, while Service Bus is designed for reliable business messages with up to 14-day retention, ordering via sessions, and transactional support.

Now let us look at Azure Event Hubs.

Azure Event Hubs is a fully managed, real-time data streaming and event ingestion service capable of ingesting millions of events per second. It is the Azure equivalent of Apache Kafka — and natively exposes a Kafka-compatible protocol endpoint, so existing Kafka producers and consumers can connect with minimal configuration changes.

The core concepts are as follows. A namespace is the container for one or more Event Hubs and provides the network endpoint. An Event Hub is a named stream, equivalent to a Kafka topic. Partitions are ordered, immutable sequences of events within an Event Hub and are the unit of parallelism — more partitions enable more parallel consumers. A consumer group is an independent view of the stream: multiple consumer groups can each read all events from the beginning without affecting each other. An offset is the position of an event within a partition, and each consumer tracks its own offset independently. Events are retained for 1 to 7 days on the Standard tier and up to 90 days on Premium and Dedicated tiers.

Partitions are the key to Event Hubs scalability. Events with the same partition key always go to the same partition, preserving ordering for that key. Each partition can be read by only one consumer per consumer group at a time, so the number of partitions determines the maximum degree of parallelism. The partition count is set at creation and cannot be changed on most tiers, so plan carefully — set it to the expected maximum number of parallel consumers.

For throughput capacity, the Standard tier uses Throughput Units where each unit provides 1 megabyte per second ingress and 2 megabytes per second egress. The Standard tier supports auto-inflate, which automatically increases throughput units when your traffic exceeds the current limit, preventing throttling without manual intervention. The Premium tier uses Processing Units with higher and more predictable throughput, V-Net integration, and customer-managed encryption keys. The Dedicated tier provides exclusive single-tenant clusters with the highest throughput and up to 10 terabytes of event retention.

Event Hubs Capture is one of its most useful features. It automatically archives the raw event stream to Azure Blob Storage or Azure Data Lake Storage Gen2 in Avro format without any additional code. The files are organised by a configurable time window. This is the foundation of a data lake ingestion pipeline — downstream tools such as Databricks, Azure Synapse, or Apache Spark process the Avro files for batch analytics alongside real-time stream processing.

Event Hubs also includes a Schema Registry — a central repository for Avro and J-S-O-N schemas. Producers register a schema once, and the schema I-D is embedded in each event. Consumers look up the schema by I-D to deserialise events correctly. This enforces schema governance across teams and enables controlled schema evolution.

For the Kafka-compatible endpoint, you connect your existing Kafka producer or consumer to the Event Hubs namespace on port 9093 using S-A-S-L S-S-L authentication. The namespace acts as the Kafka broker and the Event Hub name maps to a Kafka topic. No code changes are needed beyond updating the broker address and credentials.

To choose between the three services: if you need ordered, reliable delivery with transactions and a dead-letter queue for business workflows, use Service Bus — queues for point-to-point and topics for publish-subscribe. If you need to react to events from Azure services or your own applications and route them to multiple handlers, use Event Grid. If you need to ingest high-volume streams of telemetry, logs, or clickstream data, support replay by multiple independent consumers, or migrate a Kafka workload, use Event Hubs.

Common combinations include Event Hubs feeding Azure Functions for serverless per-event processing, Event Hubs Capture feeding Blob Storage for downstream batch analytics in Synapse or Databricks, Event Grid routing to a Service Bus queue to add reliable delivery and dead-lettering to reactive events, and Event Grid routing to Azure Functions for serverless reaction to Blob Storage uploads or resource lifecycle changes.

To summarise. Service Bus provides enterprise-grade messaging with peek-lock delivery, dead-letter queues, sessions for ordered stateful processing, duplicate detection, and transactions. Event Grid provides lightweight reactive event routing from Azure services and custom apps to many handlers with at-least-once delivery and a 24-hour retry window. Event Hubs provides high-throughput streaming with partitioned ordered retention, consumer groups for independent reads, auto-inflate for elastic throughput, Capture for zero-code archival, and Kafka protocol compatibility. The choice between them comes down to whether you need reliable business messages, reactive event routing, or high-volume stream ingestion.

In the next topic, we will look at Azure Monitor, Log Analytics, and Alerts — the observability platform that gives you visibility into the health and performance of your Azure resources.
